00:00:55.090 --> 00:00:59.470
So last time we looked at
discrete time frequency

00:00:59.470 --> 00:01:01.180
responses.

00:01:01.180 --> 00:01:02.530
Lots of things were similar.

00:01:02.530 --> 00:01:05.140
A few things were different.

00:01:05.140 --> 00:01:08.420
The first difference we saw
was that in discrete time,

00:01:08.420 --> 00:01:12.040
we like to think about complex
geometric sequences rather than

00:01:12.040 --> 00:01:14.410
complex exponential sequences.

00:01:14.410 --> 00:01:18.940
And the effect of that is
that the frequency response

00:01:18.940 --> 00:01:20.660
lives on the unit circle.

00:01:20.660 --> 00:01:23.530
So if you try to think about
a discrete time system,

00:01:23.530 --> 00:01:27.005
say, characterized
by a z-transform

00:01:27.005 --> 00:01:29.130
and think about what would
be its output when there

00:01:29.130 --> 00:01:32.500
is a sinusoidal
input, just like CT,

00:01:32.500 --> 00:01:34.270
if you have a sinusoidal
input, there's

00:01:34.270 --> 00:01:38.674
going to be a sinusoidal
output at the same frequency.

00:01:38.674 --> 00:01:40.465
But the amplitude and
phase can be shifted.

00:01:40.465 --> 00:01:44.950
But to compute the amplitude
and the phase for a DT system,

00:01:44.950 --> 00:01:48.510
you look at the unit
circle of the z-transform.

00:01:48.510 --> 00:01:52.690
That's as distinct from the
Laplace transform in CT,

00:01:52.690 --> 00:01:54.320
we looked at the j omega-axis.

00:01:54.320 --> 00:01:56.710
So now, everything we used to
say about the j omega-axis,

00:01:56.710 --> 00:01:58.930
we say about the unit circle.

00:01:58.930 --> 00:02:03.100
Other than that, things
are extremely similar.

00:02:03.100 --> 00:02:04.550
